e explains the persistence of impunity. For instance, truth telling, a first step in many responses to state violence, did not undermine the infrastructure but instead bent to it. Creative and artistic responses to revelations about the past, however, have begun to undermine the infrastructure by countering its temporality, affect, and social stigmatization and demonstrating its contingency and specific actions, policies, and processes that would begin to dismantle it. Drexler contends that an infrastructure of impunity could take hold in an established democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman rightszIndonesia. 0aPolitical violencezIndonesia. 0aTransitional justicezIndonesia. 4aANTHROPOLOGY. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  astate accountability, genocide legacies, human rights, transitional justice, legal art and performance, memory activism, youth political participation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773129?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773129423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773129/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles